data.content:
Yes — MSTest v3.4+ supports **generic `DynamicData<T1, T2>`**, which gives you compile-time type safety by using tuples instead of `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData<string, bool>(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `DynamicData` → `DynamicData<string, bool>` — type parameters match your test method signature
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — no more boxing or runtime casts
- `[…]` array syntax → `(…)` tuple syntax in the data

This catches type mismatches at compile time rather than at test runtime. Requires **MSTest 3.4+** (`MSTest.TestFramework` / `MSTest.Sdk`).
